[2
Date: Thu 25 Jan 2001 06:56:47 -0500
From: Patricia Doyle, PhD <dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
Source: Reuters, Wed 24 Jan 2001 2:19 PM ET [edited
<http://dailynews.yahoo.com/h/nm/20010124/hl/madcow_asia_1.html>

Mad Cow Crisis Has Asia Within Its Reach
----------------------------------------------
LONDON: Indonesia, Thailand, Taiwan and Sri Lanka may become the next
victims of mad cow disease after buying potentially tainted animal feed from
Britain at the height of the UK epidemic, scientists said on Wed 24 Jan
2001. Britain, which banned the feeding of crushed animal carcasses to
cattle in 1986, exported much of its stocks of feed to Europe and beyond
until a decade later, when the trade was ended.
Scientists suspect the use of meat and bone meal in feed has spread BSE, and
so UK export data may hold a key to which countries are threatened by it.
"The countries that stick out because they were importing animal feed at the
height of our [UK epidemic in the 1990s are Indonesia, India, Thailand,
Taiwan and Sri Lanka," said scientist Iain McGill, who worked at Britain's
farm ministry at the height of the BSE crisis.
McGill noted that other EU countries hit by BSE had also exported meal and
bone meal. Indonesia started importing general feedstuffs from Britain in
1991, with the largest consignment of over 20 060 tons in 1993, compared
with less than 6 tons into badly-hit Germany that year, UK customs data
showed. Thailand, Taiwan and Sri Lanka imported lesser tonnages, but the
quantities increased in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
Scientists said the spread of the disease depended on how much meat and bone
meal was included in animal feed, and how much was fed to cattle -- but the
figures did show the potential reach of BSE. "You would expect the first
cases (in Asian countries) within 3 or 4 years but it really depends on how
much they are recycling on their own," McGill said, referring to the
practice of using domestic cattle carcasses in feed. "If they are recycling
either within a species or between species ... then you might expect a peak
round about now or in the next few years -- and that depends on looking for
it."
For the United States, the risk from European feed is low, but the country's
beef industry may not be safe, McGill said. "The United States imported just
under 20 000 kg [a mere 20 tons (of UK feed) in 1989 when the epidemic
started to get going but was not at its peak, so there would be a pretty low
risk," he said. But circumstantial evidence suggested that a similar disease
in US mink might have been caused on farms where they had been fed cattle
remains. "They were recycling ... so if they had an undetected case of the
disease ... they could be more exposed from their own 'BSE' rather than from
Europe."
[Byline: Elizabeth Piper
[It should be noted that the minimum infective dose is very small, on the
order of 1/10th of a gram of nervous tissue or less. - Mod.MHJ
