Date: Fri 26 Jan 2001 13:28:49
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Agence France Presse [edited

Illegal Trade Could Let "Mad Cow" Disease Into Russia
------------------------------------------------------
MOSCOW: Russia faces a threat posed by the illegal import of meat possibly
contaminated with bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), Deputy Health
Minister Gennady Onishchenko said Thursday. His warning came after
veterinary authorities seized a 2-ton cargo of French beef suspected of
having been contaminated and illegally imported via eastern Russia. The
seizure happened in the far eastern city of Magadan, RIA Novosti reported.
Although officials had not yet detected any instance of BSE in Russia, there
was a serious danger from "the criminal import of meat in regions
contaminated by false export certificates," said Onishchenko. Mikhail
Kravtsov, the head of the agriculture ministry's veterinary department, told
journalists that beef imports were "systematically controlled at the borders
by veterinary and customs officers."
Russia has banned the import of beef from Britain, several parts of France
and other European countries. The import of all but fish-based animal feed
for livestock had also been banned, while the use of home-grown equivalents
has been outlawed since 1990, he added.
Kravtsov said that one side-effect of the financial crisis the industry had
suffered since the Soviet era had been to eliminate one of the key sources
of BSE from Russia's food chain. "We didn't have the money to buy the
animal-feed products, and our poverty was fortunate, because as a result we
do not have BSE," he added. The only Russian laboratory equipped to detect
cases of BSE had been set up in Vladimir, southeast of Moscow, in 1998.
Russia has already banned beef imports from Britain and Portugal, as well as
from certain parts of France and Ireland.
[For Russia's sake one must hope that their customs officers have adequate
salaries. - Mod.MHJ
