Date: Fri 26 Jan 2001 13:03:08
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: The Associated Press, 25 Jan 2001 11:18 p.m. EST [edited
<http://www.nandotimes.com>

Portugal, Spain, Italy & Belgium
---------------------------------------
LISBON, Portugal: Slaughterhouses across Portugal began killing the first of
50 000 cattle Thursday in an effort to purge herds of BSE. Hoping to keep
infected beef from entering the food chain and to reassure jittery
consumers, Portuguese officials ordered the slaughter of cattle older than
30 months at a rate of 3000 a week.
Meanwhile, in Spain, where beef sales have plummeted by a third since the
first case of BSE was announced in November 2000, according to the
Agriculture Ministry, 2 more cows were diagnosed with the disease Thursday.
Spain's total is now 9.
In Italy, farmers took to the streets Thursday to demand more government aid
after a second suspected case of BSE turned up.
Belgian authorities also reported the country's third case of mad cow
disease.
